at <HI>Syracuse,</HI> and the <HI>People</HI> of <HI>Tolouse</HI>
in the time<NOTE N="*" PLACE="marg">Iustin. l. 32. p. 271.</NOTE> of <HI>Brennus,</HI> ascrib'd the <HI>Cause</HI> of
their several Pests unto the <HI>Anger</HI> of their <HI>Gods</HI>
for the Sin of <HI>Sacriledge,</HI> and fled for Refuge
to <HI>Restitution,</HI> as the great <HI>means</HI> of their <HI>Reco|very.</HI>
And however <HI>Diodorus</HI> did take upon him
to assign the<NOTE N="a" PLACE="marg"><GAP DESC="foreign">. Diodor. Sic. l. 12. p. 100.</NOTE> <HI>natural</HI> Causes of the Pestilence
that reign'd at <HI>Athens,</HI> yet he assures us that the
<NOTE N="b" PLACE="marg"><GAP DESC="foreign">. Id ib. p. III.</NOTE> <HI>Athenians</HI> did look upon it as a <HI>Rod</HI> of super|natural
<PB N="163" REF="88">
contrivance. Much <HI>more</HI> should we
