<P>&sect;. 3. From the whole History of the Action,
(so farr at least as our Lord was concerned
in it,) it will be easy enough to gather These
usefull Considerations.</P>
<P>&sect;. 4. First that the Dayes being accom|plish't,
when both the <HI>Mother</HI> and her <HI>Babe</HI>
might have the freedom to goe abroad; The
first Journy they took, was not to <HI>Nazareth,</HI>
<PB N="281" REF="145">
but <HI>Ierusalem.</HI> She brought Him to <HI>God's</HI>
House before her <HI>own.</HI> Implying this Caveat
